Fold a data structure, accumulating values in some `Monoid`,
combining adjacent elements using the specified separator.

For example:

```purescript
> intercalate ", " ["Lorem", "ipsum", "dolor"]
= "Lorem, ipsum, dolor"

> intercalate "*" ["a", "b", "c"]
= "a*b*c"

> intercalate [1] [[2, 3], [4, 5], [6, 7]]
= [2, 3, 1, 4, 5, 1, 6, 7]
```

declarations.comments:
Fold a data structure from the right, keeping all intermediate results
instead of only the final result. Note that the initial value does not
appear in the result (unlike Haskell's `Prelude.scanr`).

```purescript
scanr (+) 0 [1,2,3] = [6,5,3]
scanr (flip (-)) 10 [1,2,3] = [4,5,7]
```
declarations.title: scanr

modules.name: Data.List
modules.comments:
This module defines a type of _strict_ linked lists, and associated helper
functions and type class instances.

_Note_: Depending on your use-case, you may prefer to use
`Data.Sequence` instead, which might give better performance for certain
use cases. This module is an improvement over `Data.Array` when working with
immutable lists of data in a purely-functional setting, but does not have
good random-access performance.

declarations.comments:
If the list starts with the given prefix, return the portion of the
list left after removing it, as a Just value. Otherwise, return Nothing.
* `stripPrefix (Pattern (1:Nil)) (1:2:Nil) == Just (2:Nil)`
* `stripPrefix (Pattern Nil) (1:Nil) == Just (1:Nil)`
* `stripPrefix (Pattern (2:Nil)) (1:Nil) == Nothing`

Running time: `O(n)` where `n` is the number of elements to strip.

declarations.comments:
Split a list into two parts:

1. the longest initial segment for which all elements satisfy the specified predicate
2. the remaining elements

For example,

```purescript
span (\n -> n % 2 == 1) (1 : 3 : 2 : 4 : 5 : Nil) == { init: (1 : 3 : Nil), rest: (2 : 4 : 5 : Nil) }
```

Running time: `O(n)`
declarations.title: span

declarations.comments:
Group equal, consecutive elements of a list into lists.

For example,

```purescript
group (1 : 1 : 2 : 2 : 1 : Nil) ==
  (NonEmptyList (NonEmpty 1 (1 : Nil))) : (NonEmptyList (NonEmpty 2 (2 : Nil))) : (NonEmptyList (NonEmpty 1 Nil)) : Nil
```

Running time: `O(n)`
declarations.title: group

declarations.comments:
Group equal elements of a list into lists.

For example,

```purescript
groupAll (1 : 1 : 2 : 2 : 1 : Nil) ==
  (NonEmptyList (NonEmpty 1 (1 : 1 : Nil))) : (NonEmptyList (NonEmpty 2 (2 : Nil))) : Nil
```
declarations.title: groupAll

declarations.comments:
Group equal, consecutive elements of a list into lists, using the specified
equivalence relation to determine equality.

For example,

```purescript
groupBy (\a b -> odd a && odd b) (1 : 3 : 2 : 4 : 3 : 3 : Nil) ==
  (NonEmptyList (NonEmpty 1 (3 : Nil))) : (NonEmptyList (NonEmpty 2 Nil)) : (NonEmptyList (NonEmpty 4 Nil)) : (NonEmptyList (NonEmpty 3 (3 : Nil))) : Nil
```

Running time: `O(n)`
declarations.title: groupBy

declarations.comments:
Sort, then group equal elements of a list into lists, using the provided comparison function.

```purescript
groupAllBy (compare `on` (_ `div` 10)) (32 : 31 : 21 : 22 : 11 : 33 : Nil) ==
  NonEmptyList (11 :| Nil) : NonEmptyList (21 :| 22 : Nil) : NonEmptyList (32 :| 31 : 33) : Nil
```

Running time: `O(n log n)`
declarations.title: groupAllBy


declarations.comments:

Keeps the first occurrence of each element in the input list,
in the same order they appear in the input list.

```purescript

```

Running time: `O(n log n)`

declarations.comments:
Remove duplicate elements from a list.
Keeps the first occurrence of each element in the input list,
in the same order they appear in the input list.
This less efficient version of `nub` only requires an `Eq` instance.

```purescript
nubEq 1:2:1:3:3:Nil == 1:2:3:Nil
```

Running time: `O(n^2)`
declarations.title: nubEq

declarations.comments:
Remove duplicate elements from a list, using the provided equivalence function.
Keeps the first occurrence of each element in the input list,
in the same order they appear in the input list.
This less efficient version of `nubBy` only requires an equivalence
function, rather than an ordering function.

```purescript
mod3eq = eq `on` \n -> mod n 3
nubByEq mod3eq 1:3:4:5:6:Nil == 1:3:5:Nil
```

Running time: `O(n^2)`
declarations.title: nubByEq

declarations.comments:
The 'transpose' function transposes the rows and columns of its argument.
For example,

    transpose ((1:2:3:Nil) : (4:5:6:Nil) : Nil) ==
      ((1:4:Nil) : (2:5:Nil) : (3:6:Nil) : Nil)

If some of the rows are shorter than the following rows, their elements are skipped:

    transpose ((10:11:Nil) : (20:Nil) : Nil : (30:31:32:Nil) : Nil) ==
      ((10:20:30:Nil) : (11:31:Nil) : (32:Nil) : Nil)

Running time: `O(n)` where `n` is the number of elements to take.
declarations.title: take

declarations.comments:
Take those elements from the front of a list which match a predicate.

Running time (worst case): `O(n)`
declarations.title: takeWhile

declarations.comments:
Drop the specified number of elements from the front of a list.

Running time: `O(n)` where `n` is the number of elements to drop.
declarations.title: drop

declarations.comments:
Drop those elements from the front of a list which match a predicate.

Running time (worst case): `O(n)`
declarations.title: dropWhile

declarations.comments:
Split a list into two parts:

1. the longest initial segment for which all elements satisfy the specified predicate
2. the remaining elements

For example,

```purescript
span (\n -> n % 2 == 1) (1 : 3 : 2 : 4 : 5 : Nil) == Tuple (1 : 3 : Nil) (2 : 4 : 5 : Nil)
```

Running time: `O(n)`
declarations.title: span

declarations.comments:
Group equal, consecutive elements of a list into lists.

For example,

```purescript
group (1 : 1 : 2 : 2 : 1 : Nil) == (1 : 1 : Nil) : (2 : 2 : Nil) : (1 : Nil) : Nil
```

Running time: `O(n)`
declarations.title: group

declarations.comments:
Group equal, consecutive elements of a list into lists, using the specified
equivalence relation to determine equality.

Running time: `O(n)`
declarations.title: groupBy

declarations.comments:
Returns a tuple of lists of elements which do
and do not satisfy a predicate, respectively.

Running time: `O(n)`
declarations.title: partition

declarations.comments:
Remove duplicate elements from a list.
Keeps the first occurrence of each element in the input list,
in the same order they appear in the input list.

Running time: `O(n log n)`
declarations.title: nub

declarations.comments:
Remove duplicate elements from a list based on the provided comparison function.
Keeps the first occurrence of each element in the input list,
in the same order they appear in the input list.

Running time: `O(n log n)`
declarations.title: nubBy

declarations.comments:
Remove duplicate elements from a list.

Running time: `O(n^2)`
declarations.title: nubEq

declarations.comments:
Remove duplicate elements from a list, using the specified
function to determine equality of elements.

Running time: `O(n^2)`
declarations.title: nubByEq

declarations.comments:
Calculate the union of two lists.

Running time: `O(n^2)`
declarations.title: union

declarations.comments:
Calculate the union of two lists, using the specified
function to determine equality of elements.

Running time: `O(n^2)`
declarations.title: unionBy

declarations.comments:
Delete the first occurrence of an element from a list.

Running time: `O(n)`
declarations.title: delete

declarations.comments:
Delete the first occurrence of an element from a list, using the specified
function to determine equality of elements.

Running time: `O(n)`
declarations.title: deleteBy

declarations.comments:
Delete the first occurrence of each element in the second list from the first list.

Running time: `O(n^2)`
declarations.title: difference

declarations.comments:
Calculate the intersection of two lists.

Running time: `O(n^2)`
declarations.title: intersect

declarations.comments:
Calculate the intersection of two lists, using the specified
function to determine equality of elements.

Running time: `O(n^2)`
declarations.title: intersectBy

declarations.comments:
Apply a function to pairs of elements at the same positions in two lists,
collecting the results in a new list.

If one list is longer, elements will be discarded from the longer list.

For example

```purescript
zipWith (*) (1 : 2 : 3 : Nil) (4 : 5 : 6 : 7 Nil) == 4 : 10 : 18 : Nil
```

Running time: `O(min(m, n))`
declarations.title: zipWith

declarations.comments:
A generalization of `zipWith` which accumulates results in some `Applicative`
functor.
declarations.title: zipWithA

declarations.comments:
Collect pairs of elements at the same positions in two lists.

Running time: `O(min(m, n))`
declarations.title: zip

declarations.comments:
Transforms a list of pairs into a list of first components and a list of
second components.
declarations.title: unzip

declarations.comments:
The 'transpose' function transposes the rows and columns of its argument.
For example,

    transpose ((1:2:3:nil) : (4:5:6:nil) : nil) ==
      ((1:4:nil) : (2:5:nil) : (3:6:nil) : nil)

If some of the rows are shorter than the following rows, their elements are skipped:

    transpose ((10:11:nil) : (20:nil) : nil : (30:31:32:nil) : nil) ==
      ((10:20:30:nil) : (11:31:nil) : (32:nil) : nil)
declarations.title: transpose

declarations.comments: Perform a fold using a monadic step function.

declarations.title: foldrLazy

declarations.comments: A lazy linked list.

A list is either empty (represented by the `Nil` constructor) or non-empty, in

`Cons` constructor).

The empty list.

Running time: `O(1)`

An infix alias for `cons`; attaches an element to the front of
a list.

Running time: `O(1)`
Test whether a value is not an element of a data structure.
declarations.title: notElem

declarations.comments:
Fold a data structure, accumulating values in some `Monoid`,
combining adjacent elements using the specified separator.

For example:

```purescript
> intercalate ", " ["Lorem", "ipsum", "dolor"]
= "Lorem, ipsum, dolor"

> intercalate "*" ["a", "b", "c"]
= "a*b*c"

> intercalate [1] [[2, 3], [4, 5], [6, 7]]
= [2, 3, 1, 4, 5, 1, 6, 7]
```
declarations.title: intercalate

declarations.comments: Fold a data structure, accumulating values in some `Monoid`.
declarations.title: fold

declarations.comments: Try to find an element in a data structure which satisfies a predicate mapping.
declarations.title: findMap

declarations.comments: Try to find an element in a data structure which satisfies a predicate.
declarations.title: find

declarations.comments: Test whether a value is an element of a data structure.
declarations.title: elem

declarations.comments:
`any f` is the same as `or <<< map f`; map a function over the structure,
and then get the disjunction of the results.
declarations.title: any

declarations.comments:
`all f` is the same as `and <<< map f`; map a function over the structure,
and then get the conjunction of the results.
declarations.title: all

declarations.comments:
Traverse a data structure, performing some effects encoded by an
`Apply` instance at each value, ignoring the final result.
declarations.title: traverse1_

declarations.comments:
Perform all of the effects in some data structure in the order
given by the `Foldable1` instance, ignoring the final result.
declarations.title: sequence1_
for1_

declarations.comments: Fold a data structure, accumulating values in some `Semigroup`.
declarations.title: fold1

declarations.comments: A default implementation of `traverse1` using `sequence1`.
declarations.title: traverse1Default

declarations.comments:
Fold a data structure from the right, keeping all intermediate results
instead of only the final result. Note that the initial value does not
appear in the result (unlike Haskell's `Prelude.scanr`).

```purescript
scanr (+) 0 [1,2,3] = [6,5,3]
scanr (flip (-)) 10 [1,2,3] = [4,5,7]
```
declarations.title: scanr

declarations.comments:
Fold a data structure from the left, keeping all intermediate results
instead of only the final result. Note that the initial value does not
appear in the result (unlike Haskell's `Prelude.scanl`).

```purescript
scanl (+) 0  [1,2,3] = [1,3,6]
scanl (-) 10 [1,2,3] = [9,7,4]
```
declarations.title: scanl

modules.name: Data.List.ZipList
modules.comments:
This module defines the type of _zip lists_, i.e. linked lists
with a zippy `Applicative` instance.

contents.contents:
ZipList is not Bind. Any implementation would break the associativity law.

    Possible alternatives:
        Data.List.List
        Data.List.Lazy.List

declarations.comments:
`ZipList` is a newtype around `List` which provides a zippy
`Applicative` instance.
declarations.title: ZipList
